Conversation with Gemini
im using arch on framework 13. wayland with hyprland right now. i'm launching manually. tell me the meaning of tty1, tty2 etc. what are they? now do i access them? what are they good for?

Ah, the Framework 13 with Arch and Hyprland—a classic "tinkerer’s special." Since you’re launching Hyprland manually (likely via Hyprland or startasync from the console), you're already interacting with TTYs more than the average user.

Here is the breakdown of what these "Teletypes" actually are and why they matter for your setup.

What are TTYs?
TTY stands for Teletype. Historically, these were physical electromechanical typewriters used to communicate with a mainframe. In modern Linux, we use Virtual Consoles.

Think of them as separate, full-screen terminal sessions that run directly on top of the Linux kernel, independent of your graphical environment (Wayland/Hyprland).

tty1: Usually the default console where your system boot logs appear and where you first log in.

tty2 through tty6: Additional, identical login prompts waiting for you in the background.

tty7 (and above): Typically where Graphical User Interfaces (like Hyprland or GNOME) reside once they start.

How to Access Them
You can switch between these "screens" using keyboard shortcuts. On your Framework, use:

Ctrl + Alt + F1 through F6: Switches to a specific text-only TTY.

Ctrl + Alt + F7 (or sometimes F1 or F2): Switches back to your graphical session (Hyprland).

Note: If you launched Hyprland from tty1, usually your graphical session stays "bound" to tty1 or moves to the first available slot. If you get a black screen when switching, try cycling through F1–F8.

What Are They Good For?
Since you are running a rolling release like Arch on a DIY-friendly machine like the Framework, TTYs are your "emergency exits."

1. The "Panic Room" (Recovery)
If Hyprland freezes or a Wayland compositor update breaks your config, you aren't stuck. You can jump to tty2, log in, and:

Kill the frozen process (pkill Hyprland).

Edit your config file with vim or nano.

Check logs using journalctl -xe.

2. Running Multiple Sessions
You could theoretically run Hyprland on tty1 for your main work and a completely different window manager (like Sway or even a basic X11 session) on tty2 for testing.

3. System Maintenance
When performing heavy system updates (sudo pacman -Syu), some purists prefer doing it in a TTY. If the update happens to crash your graphical environment midway through, the TTY session is more likely to remain stable, preventing a partial update (which can be a nightmare to fix).

Pro-Tip for Framework Users
Since the Framework has a high-resolution display, your TTY text might look microscopic. You can increase the font size by installing the terminus-font package and setting FONT=ter-v32b in /etc/vconsole.conf.

