wouldn't uwsm do this?

You stopped this response
wouldn't uwsm do this?

Yes, you hit the nail on the head. UWSM (Universal Wayland Session Manager) is the "official" modern solution for exactly what those custom scripts were trying to do.

Think of UWSM as the "Standardized Professional" version of a custom startasync script.

Why use UWSM instead of a manual script?
If you just run Hyprland from a TTY, your system sees one giant, messy blob of a process. If you use UWSM, your desktop becomes a organized tree of systemd units.

Feature	Manual Script / Hyprland command	UWSM
Process Management	Everything is a child of Hyprland. If Hyprland crashes, everything dies (sometimes messily).	Apps are put into their own cgroup slices. If the compositor crashes, services can stay alive or restart.
Environment Vars	You have to manually export them in .zshrc or a script.	Handles XDG and Wayland variables automatically and cleans them up on exit.
Shutdown	Can be "dirty." Apps might not get the signal to save state.	Performs a clean systemd-style shutdown of the entire graphical session.
Autostart	You use exec-once in your config.	You can use uwsm app -- [app] to launch things as proper systemd units.
How it works on your Framework/Arch setup
Since you are on Arch, Hyprland actually includes a specific wrapper called start-hyprland. However, the community is moving toward UWSM because it's compositor-agnostic (it works for Sway, Wayfire, etc., too).

To try it out:
Install it: sudo pacman -S uwsm

Launch from TTY: Instead of typing Hyprland, you would type:

Bash
uwsm start hyprland.desktop
(This looks for the desktop entry and wraps the launch in a systemd session.)

One "Catch" for Hyprland Users:
The Hyprland devs recently moved UWSM to an "experimental/advanced" recommendation status. While it’s technically superior for system management, it can be finicky with certain plugins or complex setups. For a Framework 13 user who likes Arch, it’s usually the "correct" way to do things because it integrates so well with the rest of the Linux ecosystem.

The "Framework" Advantage
Using UWSM on a laptop like the Framework is great for power management. Because every app is in its own systemd slice, you can more easily track which specific background process is eating your battery using tools like systemd-cgtop.

