how universal is it that ctrl-alt-f1 etc switch between tty's. and what are these tty's called? what's the proper sophisticated name?

In the world of Linux, we call these Virtual Consoles (or sometimes Virtual Terminals).

While "TTY" is the common shorthand we use daily, if you’re looking for the sophisticated, "I read kernel documentation for fun" name, they are formally known as VT-interfaces.

How "Universal" is it?
The short answer: Extremely universal, but with two big "ifs."

1. The Kernel Level (The Constant)
The Ctrl + Alt + F(x) shortcut is baked directly into the Linux kernel’s keyboard driver. As long as your kernel is running and hasn't completely panicked (crashed), those keys are being watched. This is why you can often switch to a TTY even when your desktop is frozen.

2. The Exception: Laptop "Fn" Keys
On your Framework 13, this is the most common "gotcha." By default, your top row of keys act as media keys (Brightness, Volume). To the hardware, F1 isn't F1—it's "Decrease Brightness."

To switch TTYs on a Framework, you usually have to hold the Fn key:

Ctrl + Alt + Fn + F3

3. The Exception: Display Managers
If you were using a "Login Screen" (like SDDM or GDM) instead of launching manually from a TTY, the behavior of F1 and F2 changes:

Usually, the login screen sits on TTY1.

Your actual desktop session might jump to TTY2 or TTY7.

Distros like Fedora and Ubuntu have moved the graphical session to TTY1 to make the boot process look "seamless," hiding the text logs entirely.

The "Sophisticated" Architecture
If you want to understand the hierarchy of these names, here is how they stack up:

Name	Level of "Sophistication"	What it actually refers to
TTY	The Nickname	Ancient shorthand for "Teletypewriter."
Virtual Console (VC)	The Standard Name	The software-emulated "screen" provided by the kernel.
VT-Session	The Technical Name	A specific session managed by systemd-logind.
PTY (Pseudo-TTY)	The "Deep Lore" Name	What you use inside Hyprland. When you open a terminal window (like Alacritty or Kitty), it’s not a TTY; it’s a "Pseudo" terminal.
Why they still exist
We keep them because they are the "Base Layer." If you ever break your graphics drivers (a rite of passage for Arch users), the Virtual Consoles are the only way to talk to the machine. They don't require a GPU driver to work; they use a simple "framebuffer" that almost any chip can render.

A Fun Trick for your Framework
Since you're on Arch, try this: Switch to a TTY (like Ctrl+Alt+F3) and run the command w.

It will show you exactly who is logged in and which TTY they are occupying. You'll likely see yourself on tty1 (where you ran Hyprland) and tty3 (the one you just switched to).

