so if i do ctrl alt f4 say on some rando linux user's machine it will immediately look broken to them?

Essentially, yes. To a "normal" computer user (the macOS or Windows crowd), hitting Ctrl + Alt + F4 on a Linux machine looks like the computer just died and traveled back to 1984.

The screen will suddenly go pitch black, and then a small, flickering white cursor will appear at the top left, followed by a stark login prompt:

arch-framework login:

Why it looks "broken"
The Disappearing Act: Their browser, their wallpaper, and their mouse cursor are gone. In their mind, the "computer" is the GUI. When the GUI disappears, the computer is "gone."

No Mouse: You can't click anything. For most people, a computer without a cursor is a brick.

The "Hacker" Aesthetic: To a rando, a black screen with white text means one of two things: a "Blue Screen of Death" equivalent or that they’re being hacked.

Is it actually dangerous?
Not at all. You haven't closed their programs; you've just switched the "channel" on the monitor. Their YouTube video is still playing audio in the background, and their unsaved Word document is still sitting in memory on TTY1 or TTY7.

However, if you do this to someone, you are essentially "locking" them out unless they know the secret handshake (Ctrl + Alt + F1 or F7) to get back.

The "Panic" Factor
If you do this on a machine running a "flicker-free" boot (like modern Fedora or Ubuntu), the transition is even more jarring because those users may have never seen a single line of code or text on their screen since they bought the laptop.

Pro-Tip: If you ever want to prank a fellow Linux user, switching them to TTY6 is the classic "low-stakes" move. It’s harmless, but it forces them to remember their TTY shortcuts to "recover" their desktop.

The "Sophisticated" Way Back
If you ever find yourself on a random machine and you've switched TTYs and can't remember which one the desktop was on, you can actually find it without guessing. Log into the TTY and run:

Bash
who
It will list the users and their TTYs. The one labeled :0 or tty1 with a "graphical" indicator is your way home.

Would you like me to show you how to disable these shortcuts in your config if you're worried about accidentally hitting them while gaming or working?

yes, how would one disable them?

To disable TTY switching, you have to decide where you want to "cut the wire." You can do it at the XKB (Keyboard Map) level, which stops the keys from being recognized as "switch" commands, or at the Kernel/Systemd level, which disables the TTYs themselves.

On Arch with Hyprland, the XKB method is the cleanest.

Method 1: The "Soft" Disable (Recommended)
You can tell Hyprland to ignore the srvrkeys (Server Keys), which include the TTY switching combos. Add this to your hyprland.conf:

Ini, TOML
input {
    kb_options = srvrkeys:none
}
What this does: It tells the X Keyboard extension to ignore the built-in "Server" actions (like Ctrl+Alt+Backspace to kill X11 or Ctrl+Alt+Fn to switch TTYs).

The Catch: This only works while Hyprland is active. If you log out or if Hyprland crashes, the keys will work again at the login prompt.

Method 2: The "Hard" Disable (Kernel Level)
If you want to make it nearly impossible to switch TTYs no matter what, you can pass a parameter to the Linux kernel.

Edit your GRUB configuration (or whatever bootloader you use): sudo nano /etc/default/grub

Find the line GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT and add kbd_mode=off or use the more specific: consoleblank=0 vt.global_cursor_default=0 (Note: Disabling VTs entirely via kernel can make debugging a broken system very difficult).

[!CAUTION] Warning: I don't recommend "hard" disabling TTYs on Arch. Since you are launching Hyprland manually, if your config has a syntax error, you'll be stuck at a black screen with no way to switch to a terminal to fix it. You'd have to boot from a Live USB to repair your files.

Method 3: Limiting the Number of TTYs
If you just want to stop "the rando" from switching to F4, F5, etc., you can tell systemd to only create one TTY.

Edit the logind configuration: sudo nano /etc/systemd/logind.conf

Uncomment and change these lines:

Ini, TOML
NAutoVTs=1
ReserveVT=1
Restart logind: sudo systemctl restart systemd-logind

This ensures that only TTY1 is active. If someone hits Ctrl+Alt+F4, nothing will happen because there is no service listening on that "channel."

Which should you use?
On a Framework 13, I suggest Method 1. It protects you from accidental presses while you're using your desktop, but keeps the "emergency exits" open if you ever need to drop to a terminal to fix a driver issue.

